# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: machine-taper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:machine-taper/2-5d-machining] In machining, **2.5D** refers to a surface which is a projection of a plane into 3rd dimension – although the object is 3-dimensional, there are no overhanging elements possible.
[src:machine-taper/2-5d-machining] Objects of this type are often represented as a contour map that gives the height (*i.e.*, thickness or depth) of the object at each point.
[src:machine-taper/2-5d-machining] 2.5D objects can be machined on a 3-axis milling machine, and do not require any of the features of a higher-axis machine to produce.
[src:machine-taper/2-5d-machining] A typical example involves an XY table that positions for each hole center, where the spindle (Z-axis) then completes a fixed cycle for drilling by plunging and retracting axially.
[src:machine-taper/2-5d-machining] The code for a 2.5D machining is significantly less than 3D contour machining, and the software and hardware requirements are (traditionally) less expensive.
[src:machine-taper/2-5d-machining] **Drilling and tapping centers** are inexpensive, limited-duty machining centers that began as a 2.5-axis market category, although many late-model ones are 3-axis because the software and hardware costs have dropped with advancing technology.
[src:machine-taper/2-5d-machining] A 2.5D image is a simplified three-dimensional (x, y, z) surface representation that contains at most one depth (z) value for every point in the (x, y) plane.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining works by forcing the abrasive particles, or grains, into the surface of the workpiece so that each particle cuts away a small bit of material.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining is similar to conventional machining, such as milling or turning, because each of the abrasive particles acts like a miniature cutting tool.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] However, unlike conventional machining the grains are much smaller than a cutting tool, and the geometry and orientation of individual grains are not well defined.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] As a result, abrasive machining is less power efficient and generates more heat.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] The grain size may be different based on the machining.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] For rough grinding, coarse abrasives are used.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] For fine grinding, fine grains (abrasives) are used.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining processes can be divided into two categories based on how the grains are applied to the workpiece.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] In bonded abrasive processes, the particles are held together within a matrix, and their combined shape determines the geometry of the finished workpiece.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] For example, in grinding the particles are bonded together in a wheel.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] As the grinding wheel is fed into the part, its shape is transferred onto the workpiece.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] In loose abrasive processes, there is no structure connecting the grains.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] They may be applied without lubrication as dry powder, or they may be mixed with a lubricant to form a slurry.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Since the grains can move independently, they must be forced into the workpiece with another object like a polishing cloth or a lapping plate.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Common abrasive processes are listed below.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] The most important property of an abrasive is its hardness.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] For abrasive grains to effectively cut, they must be significantly harder than the workpiece material.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] They can be grouped based on their hardness into two categories: conventional abrasives and superabrasives.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Conventional abrasive materials have been used since the advent of machining.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] They are made of materials that exist naturally on Earth, and they are abundant and cheap.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Conventional abrasives can suitably machine most materials.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Superabrasives are much harder than conventional abrasives.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive-machining] Since they are much more expensive, they are used when conventional abrasives will not suffice.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:machine-taper/abrasive] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] In its native habitat it blooms between July and December producing inflorescences that appear in groups of two to eight on an axillary raceme.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The spherical flower heads have a diameter of 5 to 10 mm (0.20 to 0.39 in) and contain 30 to 50 densely packed pale yellow to nearly white flowers.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Following flowering, smooth, firmly papery and glabrous seed pods form.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The curved, twisted or coiled pods have a biconvex shape with a length of 4 to 12 cm (1.6 to 4.7 in) and a width of 5 to 8 mm (0.20 to 0.31 in) and contain longitudinally arranged seeds.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The species was first formally described by the botanist Robert Brown in 1813 as a part of the William Aiton work *Hortus Kewensis*.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It was reclassified as *Racosperma melanoxylon* by Leslie Pedley in 1986 then returned to genus *Acacia* in 2006.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Several other synonyms are known including *Acacia arcuata*, *Mimosa melanoxylon* and *Acacia melanoxylon* var.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] In its native range, *A. melanoxylon* is found down the east coast of Australia from Queensland in the north, into New South Wales, through Victoria and west along the south coast of South Australia.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It is also found along the east coast of Tasmania.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It has become naturalised in Western Australia.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] In New South Wales it is widespread from coastal areas and into the Great Dividing Range but is not found further inland.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It is commonly found at higher altitudes in the Nandewar Range, Liverpool Range and around Orange in the west.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It is mostly found as a part of wet sclerophyll forest communities or near cooler rainforest communities.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The range of the tree extends from the Atherton Tableland in northern Queensland and follows the coast to around the Mount Lofty Range in South Australia and can grow in a wide range of podsols, especially in sandy loams.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Sapwood may range in colour from straw to grey-white with clear demarcation from the heartwood.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The heartwood is golden to dark brown with chocolate growth rings.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber is generally straight grained but may be wavy or interlocked.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Quartersawn surfaces may produce an attractive fiddleback figure.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The wood is lustrous and possesses a fine to medium texture.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The name of the wood may refer to dark stains on the hands of woodworkers, caused by the high levels of tannin in the timber.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Australian blackwood seasons easily with some possible cupping when boards are inadequately restrained.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber produces little movement once seasoned.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber is susceptible to attacked by furniture beetles, termites and powder-post beetles (sapwood) due to its physical resistance to effective preservative treatments.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber provides very high chatoyance, with an average value above 26 PZC.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] has been introduced to many countries for forestry plantings and as an ornamental tree.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It now is present in Africa, Asia, Europe, Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean, South America and the United States.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It is a declared noxious weed species in South Africa and is a pest in Portugal's Azores Islands.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It was also recently listed by the California Invasive Plant Council (Cal-IPC) as an invasive weed that may cause limited impact (Knapp 2003).
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Its use as a street tree is being phased out in some locales because of the damage it often causes to pavements and underground plumbing.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] In some regions of Tasmania, blackwood is now considered a pest.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Indigenous Australians use many parts of *A. melanoxylon* for a variety of purposes.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Seeds are harvested and consumed as a common bush tucker food, and leaves can be used as a soap or fishing poison.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The bark is either harvested to make string or prepared as a traditional analgesic, while wood is often used to make clap sticks, spear-throwers and shields.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The live plant is also employed as a fire barrier in rural settings when grown amongst other fire-resistant species.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Blackwood timber is commercially milled for wood paneling, furniture, joinery and cabinetry, tool handles, boat-building, inlaid boxes and wooden kegs.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] It is often qualitatively compared to walnut hardwood, and its physical properties are well-suited for shaping with steam.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] The bark contains a tannin content of about 20%, and is often engineered to produce decorative wood veneer.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] Plain and figured Australian blackwood is used for musical instruments; in particular, guitars, drums, Hawaiian ukuleles, violin bows and organ pipes.
[src:machine-taper/acacia-melanoxylon] More recently, blackwood has seen an increasing value as a substitute for koa wood.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] A combination of both precision and trueness, accounting for the two types of observational error (random and systematic), so that high accuracy requires both high precision and high trueness.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] This usage corresponds to ISO's definition of *accuracy* (trueness and precision).
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In the fields of science and engineering, the accuracy of a measurement system is the degree of closeness of measurements of a quantity to that quantity's true value.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] The precision of a measurement system, related to reproducibility and repeatability, is the degree to which repeated measurements under unchanged conditions show the same results.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Although the two words precision and accuracy can be synonymous in colloquial use, they are deliberately contrasted in the context of the scientific method.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] The field of statistics, where the interpretation of measurements plays a central role, prefers to use the terms *bias* and *variability* instead of accuracy and precision: bias is the amount of inaccuracy and variability is the amount of imprecision.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] A measurement system can be accurate but not precise, precise but not accurate, neither, or both.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] For example, if an experiment contains a systematic error, then increasing the sample size generally increases precision but does not improve accuracy.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] The result would be a consistent yet inaccurate string of results from the flawed experiment.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Eliminating the systematic error improves accuracy but does not change precision.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] A measurement system is considered *valid* if it is both *accurate* and *precise*.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Related terms include *bias* (non-random or directed effects caused by a factor or factors unrelated to the independent variable) and *error* (random variability).
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] The terminology is also applied to indirect measurements—that is, values obtained by a computational procedure from observed data.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In addition to accuracy and precision, measurements may also have a measurement resolution, which is the smallest change in the underlying physical quantity that produces a response in the measurement.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In numerical analysis, accuracy is also the nearness of a calculation to the true value; while precision is the resolution of the representation, typically defined by the number of decimal or binary digits.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In military terms, accuracy refers primarily to the accuracy of fire (*justesse de tir*), the precision of fire expressed by the closeness of a grouping of shots at and around the centre of the target.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] A shift in the meaning of these terms appeared with the publication of the ISO 5725 series of standards in 1994, which is also reflected in the 2008 issue of the BIPM International Vocabulary of Metrology (VIM), items 2.13 and 2.14.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] According to ISO 5725-1, the general term "accuracy" is used to describe the closeness of a measurement to the true value.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] When the term is applied to sets of measurements of the same measurand, it involves a component of random error and a component of systematic error.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In this case trueness is the closeness of the mean of a set of measurement results to the actual (true) value, that is the systematic error, and precision is the closeness of agreement among a set of results, that is the random error.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] ISO 5725-1 and VIM also avoid the use of the term "bias", previously specified in BS 5497-1, because it has different connotations outside the fields of science and engineering, as in medicine and law.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In industrial instrumentation, accuracy is the measurement tolerance, or transmission of the instrument and defines the limits of the errors made when the instrument is used in normal operating conditions.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Ideally a measurement device is both accurate and precise, with measurements all close to and tightly clustered around the true value.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] The accuracy and precision of a measurement process is usually established by repeatedly measuring some traceable reference standard.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Such standards are defined in the International System of Units (abbreviated SI from French: *Système international d'unités*) and maintained by national standards organizations such as the National Institute of Standards and Technology in the United States.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] This also applies when measurements are repeated and averaged.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In that case, the term standard error is properly applied: the precision of the average is equal to the known standard deviation of the process divided by the square root of the number of measurements averaged.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Further, the central limit theorem shows that the probability distribution of the averaged measurements will be closer to a normal distribution than that of individual measurements.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] A common convention in science and engineering is to express accuracy and/or precision implicitly by means of significant figures.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Where not explicitly stated, the margin of error is understood to be one-half the value of the last significant place.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] For instance, a recording of 843.6 m, or 843.0 m, or 800.0 m would imply a margin of 0.05 m (the last significant place is the tenths place), while a recording of 843 m would imply a margin of error of 0.5 m (the last significant digits are the units).
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] A reading of 8,000 m, with trailing zeros and no decimal point, is ambiguous; the trailing zeros may or may not be intended as significant figures.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] To avoid this ambiguity, the number could be represented in scientific notation: 8.0 × 103 m indicates that the first zero is significant (hence a margin of 50 m) while 8.000 × 103 m indicates that all three zeros are significant, giving a margin of 0.5 m.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Similarly, one can use a multiple of the basic measurement unit: 8.0 km is equivalent to 8.0 × 103 m.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] It indicates a margin of 0.05 km (50 m).
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] However, reliance on this convention can lead to false precision errors when accepting data from sources that do not obey it.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] For example, a source reporting a number like 153,753 with precision +/- 5,000 looks like it has precision +/- 0.5.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Under the convention it would have been rounded to 150,000.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Alternatively, in a scientific context, if it is desired to indicate the margin of error with more precision, one can use a notation such as 7.54398(23) × 10−10 m, meaning a range of between 7.54375 and 7.54421 × 10−10 m.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In engineering, precision is often taken as three times Standard Deviation of measurements taken, representing the range that 99.73% of measurements can occur within.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] For example, an ergonomist measuring the human body can be confident that 99.73% of their extracted measurements fall within ± 0.7 cm - if using the GRYPHON processing system - or ± 13 cm - if using unprocessed data.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In this context, the concepts of trueness and precision as defined by ISO 5725-1 are not applicable.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] One reason is that there is not a single “true value” of a quantity, but rather two possible true values for every case, while accuracy is an average across all cases and therefore takes into account both values.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] However, the term *precision* is used in this context to mean a different metric originating from the field of information retrieval (see § In information systems).
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] When computing accuracy in multiclass classification, accuracy is simply the fraction of correct classifications: ${\text{Accuracy}}={\frac {\text{correct classifications}}{\text{all classifications}}}$ This is usually expressed as a percentage.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] For example, if a classifier makes ten predictions and nine of them are correct, the accuracy is 90%.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Accuracy is sometimes also viewed as a *micro metric*, to underline that it tends to be greatly affected by the particular class prevalence in a dataset and the classifier's biases.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Furthermore, it is also called top-1 accuracy to distinguish it from top-5 accuracy, common in convolutional neural network evaluation.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] To evaluate top-5 accuracy, the classifier must provide relative likelihoods for each class.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] When these are sorted, a classification is considered correct if the correct classification falls anywhere within the top 5 predictions made by the network.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Top-5 accuracy was popularized by the ImageNet challenge.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] It is usually higher than top-1 accuracy, as any correct predictions in the 2nd through 5th positions will not improve the top-1 score, but do improve the top-5 score.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In psychometrics and psychophysics, the term *accuracy* is interchangeably used with validity and *constant error*.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] *Precision* is a synonym for reliability and *variable error*.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] The validity of a measurement instrument or psychological test is established through experiment or correlation with behavior.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Reliability is established with a variety of statistical techniques, classically through an internal consistency test like Cronbach's alpha to ensure sets of related questions have related responses, and then comparison of those related question between reference and target population.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In logic simulation, a common mistake in evaluation of accurate models is to compare a logic simulation model to a transistor circuit simulation model.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] This is a comparison of differences in precision, not accuracy.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Precision is measured with respect to detail and accuracy is measured with respect to reality.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Commonly used metrics include the notions of precision and recall.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In this context, precision is defined as the fraction of documents correctly retrieved compared to the documents retrieved (true positives divided by true positives plus false positives), using a set of ground truth relevant results selected by humans.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Recall is defined as the fraction of documents correctly retrieved compared to the relevant documents (true positives divided by true positives plus false negatives).
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Less commonly, the metric of accuracy is used, is defined as the fraction of documents correctly classified compared to the documents (true positives plus true negatives divided by true positives plus true negatives plus false positives plus false negatives).
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] None of these metrics take into account the ranking of results.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Ranking is very important for web search engines because readers seldom go past the first page of results, and there are too many documents on the web to manually classify all of them as to whether they should be included or excluded from a given search.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Adding a cutoff at a particular number of results takes ranking into account to some degree.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] The measure precision at k, for example, is a measure of precision looking only at the top ten (k=10) search results.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] More sophisticated metrics, such as discounted cumulative gain, take into account each individual ranking, and are more commonly used where this is important.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] In cognitive systems, accuracy and precision is used to characterize and measure results of a cognitive process performed by biological or artificial entities where a cognitive process is a transformation of data, information, knowledge, or wisdom to a higher-valued form.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] (DIKW Pyramid) Sometimes, a cognitive process produces exactly the intended or desired output but sometimes produces output far from the intended or desired.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] Furthermore, repetitions of a cognitive process do not always produce the same output.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] *Cognitive accuracy* (CA) is the propensity of a cognitive process to produce the intended or desired output.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] *Cognitive precision* (CP) is the propensity of a cognitive process to produce the same output.
[src:machine-taper/accuracy-and-precision] To measure augmented cognition in human/cog ensembles, where one or more humans work collaboratively with one or more cognitive systems (cogs), increases in cognitive accuracy and cognitive precision assist in measuring the degree of cognitive augmentation.
[src:machine-taper/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:machine-taper/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:machine-taper/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:machine-taper/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:machine-taper/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:machine-taper/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:machine-taper/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:machine-taper/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:machine-taper/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:machine-taper/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:machine-taper/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:machine-taper/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:machine-taper/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:machine-taper/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:machine-taper/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:machine-taper/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:machine-taper/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:machine-taper/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:machine-taper/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:machine-taper/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:machine-taper/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:machine-taper/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:machine-taper/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:machine-taper/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] As a Standards Development Organization, ASME continues to develop and maintains nearly 600 codes and standards in a wide range of disciplines including pressure technology, nuclear plants, elevators / escalators, construction, engineering design, and performance testing.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Machine Tool standards are developed and maintained by ASME B5 Committee, which operates under ASME's Board on Standardization and Testing.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee currently meets once a year in various locations throughout the United States.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The meeting is generally held in November and is open to the public.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The B5 Technical Committees usually meet in conjunction with the B5 Standards Committee.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Some B5 Technical Committees also meet separately in different locations throughout the year.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee and its Technical Committees are composed of experts in the field of machine tools.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Members of the B5 Standards Committee are classified in the following interest classes: Producer/Manufacturer, Regulatory, Services, General Interest, and User.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The B5 Committee works on writing new ASME American National Standards, and revising current ASME B5 and B94 standards.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee operates under procedures of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The celebration of the 100th meeting in 2022 will mark the 100th consecutive year the ASME B5 committee has met.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The following historical information marks only the beginning stages of copious collaborative work and continuous publication, review, and revision of ASME B5 Standards.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] On May 13, 1914, the ASME Committee on Meetings, Subcommittee on Machine Shop Practice began discussion on standardization of machine shop practices.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] It wasn't until September 1922 under the procedure of American Standards Association, the B5 committee was organized as a committee dedicated to machine tools.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] B5 was sponsored by the National Machine Tool Builders’ Association, the Society of Automotive Engineers, Metal Cutting Tool Institute, and The American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] On December 2, 1937, the standard for Adjustable Adapters for Multiple Spindle Drilling Heads this standard was approved by the American Standards Association and designated as American Standard (ASA B5.11-1937).
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Work on the standardization of T-slots started in 1924 and a tentative standard was published in 1927.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The first official American Standard for T-slots came in 1941.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] 11 was organized in New York on December 4, 1928, and B5 Technical Committee No.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] 4 on Spindle Noses was organized on December 5, 1928.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] These two committees worked in close cooperation with each other and with manufacturers and users of engine lathes, turret lathes and automatic lathes in developing standards for spindle noses and chucks.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] 3 on the Standardization of Machine Tapers was appointed in August, 1926, and held its organization meeting in September, 1926, in New Haven, Conn.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Three American tapers then in use, the Brown & Sharpe (1860), Morse (1862), and Jarno (1889), and the taper series adopted by William Sellers & Co.(1862) were combined into a compromise standard series which contained twenty-two (22) self-holding taper sizes.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The first edition of the Spindle Noses and Tool Shanks for Milling Machines standard, known as B5.18-1943, resulted from intensive effort dating back to 1926 by a special group of milling machine manufacturers.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] The effort to establish an American standard for Ball Screws began in July 1971 out of a need to obtain a consensus opinion relative to proposals for standardization of ball screw assemblies within the ISO/TC39 sub-committee Working Group 7.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Out of this, the subcommittee TC43 was organized with members representing manufacturers, users of ball screws, and others of general interest.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] TC43 produced ANSI B5.48, which was approved as an American National Standard and published in 1977.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Technical subcommittees under ASME B5 address the formulation and maintenance of standards in particular disciplines within the scope of the B5 charter.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Membership includes a carefully balanced representation in various interest classifications so that no one group dominates.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Some examples of the various interest classifications are: users, manufacturers, consultants, insurance interests, universities, testing laboratories, and government regulatory agencies.
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] There are over 40 Standards that are periodically reviewed to ensure they reflect new developments and technical advances (e.g., new materials, new designs and new applications).
[src:machine-taper/asme-b5] Several new standards are under development or being considered in the areas of Tool Holder Interfaces, Machine Performance Evaluation, Micromachining, Energy Assessment, and Robotics.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] A **machine taper** is a system for securing cutting tools, workholders or toolholders in the spindle of a machine tool or power tool.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] A male member of conical form (that is, with a taper) fits into the female socket, which has a matching taper of equal angle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Almost all machine tool spindles, and many power tool spindles, have a taper as their primary method of attachment for tools.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Even on many drill presses, handheld drills, and lathes, which have chucks (such as a drill chuck or collet chuck), the chuck is attached by a taper.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] On drills, drill presses, and milling machines, the male member is the tool shank or toolholder shank, and the female socket is integral with the spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] On lathes, the male may belong to the tool or to the spindle; spindle noses may have male tapers, female tapers, or both.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Machine tool operators must be able to install or remove tool bits quickly and easily.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] A lathe, for example, has a rotating spindle in its headstock, to which one may want to mount a spur drive or work in a collet.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Another example is a drill press, to which an operator may want to mount a bit directly, or using a drill chuck.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Virtually all milling machines, from the oldest manual machines up to the most modern CNC machines, use tooling that is piloted on a tapered surface.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The machine taper is a simple, low-cost, highly repeatable, and versatile tool mounting system.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] It provides indexability, as tools can be quickly changed but are precisely located both concentrically and axially by the taper.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] It also allows high power transmission across the interface, which is needed for milling.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Machine tapers can be grouped into **self-holding** and **self-releasing** classes.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] With self-holding tapers, the male and female wedge together and bind to each other to the extent that the forces of drilling can be resisted without a drawbar, and the tool will stay in the spindle when idle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] It is driven out with a wedge when a tool change is needed.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Morse and Jacobs tapers are an example of the self-holding variety.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] With self-releasing tapers, the male will not stick in the female without a drawbar holding it there.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] However, with good drawbar force, it is very solidly immobile.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] NMTB/CAT, BT and HSK are examples of the self-releasing variety.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] For light loads (such as encountered by a lathe tailstock or a drill press), tools with self-holding tapers are simply slipped onto or into the spindle; the pressure of the spindle against the workpiece drives the tapered shank tightly into the tapered hole.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The friction across the entire surface area of the interface provides a large amount of torque transmission, so that drawbars, splines or keys are not required.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] For use with heavy loads (such as encountered by a milling machine spindle), there is usually a key to prevent rotation and/or a threaded section, which is engaged by a drawbar that engages either the threads or the head of a pull stud that is screwed into them.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The drawbar is then tightened, drawing the shank firmly into the spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The draw-bar is important on milling machines as the transverse force component would otherwise cause the tool to wobble out of the taper.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] All machine tapers are sensitive to chips, nicks (dents), and dirt.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] They will not locate accurately, and the self-holding variety will not hold reliably, if such problems interfere with the seating of the male into the female with firm contact over the whole conical surface.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Machinists are trained on keeping tapers clean and handling them in ways that prevent them from being nicked by other tools.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] CNC tool-changing cycles usually include a compressed-air blast while one toolholder is being swapped with the next.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The air blast tends to blow away chips that might otherwise end up interfering between the toolholder and spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Tools with a tapered shank are inserted into a matching tapered socket and pushed or twisted into place.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] In some cases, the friction fit needs to be made stronger, as with the use of a drawbar, essentially a long bolt that holds the tool into the socket with more force than is possible by other means.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Caution needs to be exercised in the usual drilling machine or lathe situation, which provides no drawbar to pull the taper into engagement, if a tool is used requiring a high torque but providing little axial resistance.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] An example would be the use of a large diameter drill to slightly enlarge an existing hole.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] In this situation, there may be considerable rotary loading.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] In contrast, the cutting action will require very little thrust or feed force.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Thrust helps to keep the taper seated and provides essential frictional coupling.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The tang is not engineered to withstand twisting forces which are sufficient to cause the taper to slip, and will frequently break off in this situation.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] This will allow the tool to spin in the female taper, which is likely to damage it.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Morse taper reamers are available to alleviate minor damage.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Tapered shanks "stick" in a socket best when both the shank and the socket are clean.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Shanks can be wiped clean, but sockets, being deep and inaccessible, are best cleaned with a specialized taper cleaning tool which is inserted, twisted, and removed.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Tapered shank tools are removed from a socket using different approaches, depending on the design of the socket.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] In drill presses and similar tools, the tool is removed by inserting a wedge shaped block of metal called a "drift" into a rectangular shaped cross hole through the socket and tapping it.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] As the cross section of the drift gets larger when the drift is driven further in, the result is that the drift, bearing against the foremost edge of the tang, pushes the tool out.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] In many lathe tailstocks, the tool is removed by fully withdrawing the quill into the tailstock, which brings the tool up against the end of the leadscrew or an internal stud, separating the taper and releasing the tool.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Where the tool is retained by a drawbar, as in some mill spindles, the drawbar is partially unthreaded with a wrench and then tapped with a hammer, which separates the taper, at which point the tool can be further unthreaded and removed.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Some mill spindles have a captive drawbar which ejects the tool when actively unscrewed past the loose stage; these do not require tapping.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] For simple sockets with open access to the back end, a drift punch is inserted axially from behind and the tool tapped out.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The standards are grouped into families that may include different sizes.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The taper within a family may or may not be consistent.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The Jarno and NMTB tapers are consistent, but the Jacobs and Morse families vary.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] There are adaptors available to allow the use of one type of taper tooling, e.g.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Morse, on a machine with a different taper, e.g.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] R8 or vice versa, and simpler adaptors consisting of an externally and internally tapered sleeve to allow a small Morse tool to be used in a machine of larger bore.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] One of the first uses of tapers was to mount drill bits directly to machine tools, such as in the tailstock of a lathe, although later drill chucks were developed that held parallel shank drill bits.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Brown & Sharpe tapers (Abbreviated BS or B&S), standardized by the company of the same name, are an alternative to the more-commonly seen Morse taper.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Like the Morse, these have a series of sizes, from 1 to 18, with 7, 9 and 11 being the most common.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Actual taper on these lies within a narrow range close to .500 inches per foot (41.67 mm per meter).
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The Jacobs Taper (abbreviated JT) is commonly used to secure drill press chucks to an arbor.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The taper angles are not consistent varying from 1.41° per side for No.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] There are also several sizes between No.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Jarno tapers use a greatly simplified scheme.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The rate of taper is 1:20 on diameter, in other words 0.600" on diameter per foot, .050" on diameter per inch.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Tapers range from a Number 2 to a Number 20.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The diameter of the big end in inches is always the taper size divided by 8, the small end is always the taper size divided by 10 and the length is the taper size divided by 2.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The Morse taper (Abbreviated MT) was developed by Stephen A.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Morse, based in New Bedford, Massachusetts, in the mid-1860s.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Since then, it has evolved to encompass smaller and larger sizes and has been adopted as a standard by numerous organizations, including the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) as ISO 296 and the German Institute for Standardization (DIN) as DIN 228–1.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] It is one of the most widely used types, and is particularly common on the shank of taper-shank twist drills and machine reamers, in the spindles of industrial drill presses, and in the tailstocks of lathes.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The taper angle of the Morse taper varies somewhat with size but is typically 1.49 degrees (around 3 degrees included).
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Some modular orthopedic total hip implants use a Morse taper to mate components together.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Similarly, some dental implants use a Morse taper to connect components.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Morse tapers come in eight sizes identified by whole numbers between 0 and 7, and one half-size (4.5, which is less common, but used on some medium sized lathes where a slightly larger taper than MT4 is needed without jumping to the much larger MT5).
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Often the designation is abbreviated as "MT" followed by a digit, for example a Morse taper number 4 would be MT4 (another common abbreviation that comes from German is "MK" for Morsekegel).
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The MT2 taper is the size most often found in drill presses up to 13 mm (1⁄2") capacity.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Stub (short) versions, the same taper angle but a little over half the usual length, are occasionally encountered for the whole number sizes from 1 through 5.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] There are standards for these, which among other things are sometimes used in lathe head stocks to preserve a larger spindle through-hole.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Self-holding tapers rely on a heavy preponderance of axial load over radial load to transmit high torques.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Problems may arise using large drills in relation to the shank, if the pilot hole is too large.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The threaded style is essential for any sideloading, particularly milling.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The only exception is that such unfavourable situations can be simulated to remove a jammed shank.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Permitting chatter will help release the grip.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The acute (narrow) taper angle can result in such jamming with heavy axial loads, or over long periods.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] End-milling cutters with a Morse taper shank with a tang are occasionally seen: for security these must be used with a C-collar or similar, fitting into the neck between cutter and shank, and pulling back against the large end of the taper.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The taper itself is roughly 52 mm per meter (5/8" per foot, or just under 1.5 degrees), but exact ratios and dimensions for the various sizes of tang type tapers are given below.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] B-series tapers are a DIN standard (DIN 238) typically used for fitting chucks on their arbors, like the older Jacobs taper series.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The National Machine Tool Builders Association (now called the Association for Manufacturing Technology) defined a steep taper that is commonly used on milling machines.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The taper is variously referred to as NMTB, NMT or NT.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The taper is 3.500 inches per foot and is also referred to as "7 in 24" or 7/24; the computed angle is 16.5943 degrees.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] All NMTB tooling has this taper but the tooling comes in different sizes: NMTB-10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50 and 60.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] These tapers were apparently also specified in ASA (now ANSI) B5.10-1943.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] NMTB is a "self releasing" or "fast" taper.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Unlike the more acute self holding tapers above, such tapers are not designed to transmit high torque; high torques are carried by driving keys engaging slots on the flange.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The purpose is to allow a quick and easy change between different tools (either automatically or by hand) while ensuring the tool or toolholder will be tightly and rigidly connected to the spindle, and accurately coaxial with it.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The larger end adjacent to the tool makes for more rigidity than is possible with Morse or R8 tapers fitted to comparable machines.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Patent 1794361 (filed 25 March 1927) describes milling machine spindle and tool shapes using a steep taper.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The patent was assigned to Kearney & Trecker Corporation, Brown & Sharpe, and Cincinnati Milling Machine Company.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The patent wanted a taper that would freely release the tool and found that a taper of 3.5 in 12 had that property.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The patent also used the keys and slots and a tail on the tool shank to prevent the tool shank from falling out of a horizontal mill's spindle while the operator connected the drawbar.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] ANSI B5.18-1972 specifies some essential dimensions for milling machine spindles and tool shanks using taper sizes 30, 40, 45, 50, 60.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The specifications describe the position of the driving key and flange and the thread of the drawbar bolt that holds the shank in the spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The tooling is referred to as Quick Change; National Machine Tool Builders' Association, 1927; NMTB; American Standard Machine Taper, ANSI B5.18; DIN 2080 / IS 2340; ISO R 290–2583.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] There are slight variations in threads and flanges (JIS B 6339: MAS 403); and the European standards (e.g., **ISO taper,** DIN 2080) use metric drawbar threads.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Aside from the drawbar threads the above standards are physically compatible with each other in most cases.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The NMTB tool shanks had the 7 in 24 taper, but they also had a constant diameter tail (pilot) at the end of the shank that was described in the 1927 patent.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Subsequent design variations dropped the tail (making the shank shorter) and put a V-groove in the flange that aided automated tool changing.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Modern designs started using power drawbars that gripped pull studs (also known as retention knobs) that were screwed into the tool shank rather than screw-in drawbars.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The power drawbar would grip the pull stud rather than screwing into the tool shank, allowing for faster automatic tool changes.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The more modern toolholder designs became known as the Caterpillar "V-Flange", CAT, V-Flange, (ANSI B5.50,) this was later codified under ISO 7388-1.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Once again, there are modest variations in the tooling.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Although the basic taper dimensions are the same, there are differences in the flanges, v-groove sizes, drive keyways, and pull stud dimensions; the international versions use metric sizes, and metric stud threads particularly.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] HSK toolholders were developed in the early 1990s.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] HSK stands for *Hohlschaftkegel*; German for "hollow shank tapers".
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Steep tapers (e.g., NMTB and derivatives) tend to lose rigidity and accuracy at high speed, as their solid shanks are stiffer than the spindles they fit into.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Under high centrifugal force, the spindle expands more than the toolholder which changes the overall length: That is, as the spindle spreads outward, the toolholder tends to move deeper into the spindle along the z-axis, which can cause the production of parts that are out-of-tolerance.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Moreover, the thinnest part of the spindle interface is the front shoulder, which tends to expand the most.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] This zone engages the stiffest part of the holder where radial forces are also the highest.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] This significantly reduces the stiffness of the spindle interface allowing more deflection of the holder under cutting load, particularly with long tools.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The holder can "rock" or "walk" slightly from side to side, by way of elastic deformation.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Usually this causes poor runout accuracy, more chatter, and unduly short tool life.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] In the most extreme case it can cause Fretting wear on the spindle surface due to slight relative motion of the holder against the female interface.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] HSK's hollow shank is deliberately thin and flexible, so it expands more than the spindle and tightens when rotating at high speed.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Furthermore, the HSK holder is dual contact: It engages with the spindle on both the taper and the top of the flange which resists axial movement when thermal growth and/or centrifugal force of the spindle occurs.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The flexibility is also used to provide accurate axial location.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] An HSK toolholder has both a tapered shank, and a flange with a mating surface.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The shank is short (about half as long as other machine tapers), with a shallow taper, the shank is 1:9.98 and the receiver is 1:10, and slightly too large to allow the flange to seat fully in the socket.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The thin walls, short shank and shallow taper provide a large opening in the back of the tool.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] An expanding collet fits in there, and mates with 30° chamfer inside the shank.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] As the drawbar retracts, it expands the collet and pulls the shank back into the socket, compressing the shank until the flange seats against the front of the spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] This provides a stiff, repeatable connection because it utilizes the centrifugal force inside the spindle for security and rigidity.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] As centrifugal forces increase the expanding collet within the HSK forces the walls of the toolholder shank to stay in contact with the spindle wall.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The HSK design was developed as a nonproprietary standard.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The working group that produced the HSK standard consisted of representatives from academia, the Association of German Tool Manufacturing and a group of international companies and end users.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The results were the German DIN standards 69063 for the spindle and 69893 for the shank.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The HSK working group did not adopt a specific product design, but rather a set of standards that defined HSK toolholders for different applications.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The group defined a total of six HSK shank forms, in 9 sizes.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Sizes are identified by the diameter of the shank's flange in millimeters.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] These diameters are taken from the R10′ series of preferred numbers, from 25 to 160 mm.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Today, the shank forms are designated by the letters A through F and T.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The main differences between the forms are the positions of the drive slots, gripper-locating slots, coolant holes and the area of the flange.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The B-form shank is a variant for high-torque applications, and has a flange one size larger relative to its shaft diameter.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Forms C and D are simplified variants of A and B for manual use, eliminating features to accommodate automatic tool changers like a V-groove and associated orientation slots, and a recess for an RFID chip.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Forms E and F flanges and tapers are similar to forms A and B, but designed for very high speed machining (20,000 rpm and up) of light materials by eliminating all asymmetric features to minimize imbalance and vibration.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] This permits non-rotating lathe tooling to be held accurately.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] An HSK connection depends on a combination of axial clamping forces and taper-shank interference.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] All these forces are generated and controlled by the mating components' design parameters.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The shank and spindle both must have precisely mating tapers and faces that are square to the taper's axis.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] All use some mechanism to amplify the clamping action of equally spaced collet segments.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] When the toolholder is clamped into the spindle, the drawbar force produces a firm metal-to-metal contact between the shank and the ID of the clamping unit.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] An additional application of drawbar force positively locks the two elements together into a joint with a high level of radial and axial rigidity.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] As the collet segments rotate, the clamping mechanism gains centrifugal force.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The HSK design actually harnesses centrifugal force to increase joint strength.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Centrifugal force also causes the thin walls of the shank to deflect radially at a faster rate than the walls of the spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] This contributes to a secure connection by guaranteeing strong contact between the shank and the spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The automotive and aerospace industries are the largest users of HSK toolholders.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Another industry that is seeing increasing use is the mold and die industry.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] PSC stands for "Polygonal Shank Conical." Originally developed in 1989 by Ken Andersson working for the Swedish machine tool company Sandvik Coromant AB.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Therefore, Sandvik sought certification for the style of interface from ISO international in the mid-2000s.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] In 2007 PSC was published under ISO 26623.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Thus, toolholders and spindles that conform to ISO 26623 are fully compatible with brand name Capto tooling.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] PSC shares several design features of HSK such as a short hollow shank, additional contact of the flange with the face of the female spindle interface, and clamping by an internal expanding collet.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] However PSC features a unique non-circular shank with a cross sectional resembling a Reuleax Triangle with filleted corners, while the hollow central counterbore is cylindrical.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] PSC also features a shallow 2.88° taper of the triangular shank compared to 5.72°(1:10) of HSK.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] One aspect PSC shares with NMTB styles, and differs from HSK, in having a more limited number of sizes that are near identical in form, since it is designed to have a wider range of application.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Torque transmission is accomplished by means of pressure on the corners of the shank, rather than drive keys and/or friction between the spindle & shank.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] In addition to axial and radial rigidity, this provides better angular repeatability and improved torsional rigidity over other interfaces.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Pressures resulting from applied torque improve rigidity because they are applied over a much larger area of the shank.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The conical tapered shank allows a slight interference fit with the spindle rather than requiring a clearance for disassembly, improving angular repeatability.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] PSC is popular for combination turn-mill centers with a single 3-4axis tool spindle and also CNC Turret lathes due to its superior angular repeatability and off-axis torsional rigidity.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] It can support static/fixed off-axis turning tools and is also suitable for turret lathes with a large number of driven tool stations.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] This provides a single quick-change interface for both live cutters and static tools.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] It can replace conventional square or round shank static tools, resulting in a much faster setup time when swapping worn tools.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] PSC provides superior performance for live/driven boring heads, enabling higher feeds and better surface finishes.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] This taper was designed by Bridgeport Machines, Inc. for use in its milling machines.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] R8 tapers are not self-holding, so they require a drawbar extending up through the spindle to the top of the machine to prevent loosening when lateral forces are encountered.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] They are also keyed (see image) to prevent rotation during insertion and removal, although it is the taper that transmits torque in use.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The drawbar thread is typically 7⁄16″–20 tpi (UNF).
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] (source, Bridgeport Manufacturer) The diameter of the parallel locating portion is not a "fractional inch" size like the other dimensions and is 0.949″ to 0.9495″.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Tools with an R8 taper are inserted directly into the machine's spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] R8 collets are typically used to hold tooling with round shanks, although any shape can be held if the collet has the corresponding shape cut in it.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The collets have a precision bore with axial compression slots for holding cutting tools and are threaded for the drawbar.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The R8 system is commonly used with collets ranging in size from 1⁄8″ to 3⁄4″ in diameter or tool holders with the same or slightly larger diameters.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The collets or tool holders are placed directly into the spindle and the drawbar is tightened into the top of the collet or tool holder from above the spindle.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] Other tools such as drill chucks, fly cutters, indexable insert cutters, etc. may have an R8 taper shank built into or added to the tool.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The R8 taper is commonly encountered on Bridgeport and similar turret mills from the US, or on (very common) copies of these mills from elsewhere.
[src:machine-taper/machine-taper] The popularity is due in large part to the success of Bridgeport and other mills that were closely modeled after it and produced throughout much of the 20th century.
